{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01UbbjigMtou7NfSs3FP5KVn","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Questions and answers\n2\t\n3\tThe goal of this file is to have a place to easily commit answers to questions\n4\tin a way that's easily searchable, and can make its way into official\n5\tdocumentation later.\n6\t\n7\t## Q: When I customize the Ignition generated by the installer, how does the MCO handle that?\n8\t\n9\tThis is a supported operation.  Today, the MCO does not have good support for \"per node\"\n10\tconfiguration, and configuring things like static IP addresses and partition layouts\n11\tby customizing the Ignition makes sense.\n12\t\n13\tHowever, it's important to understand that these custom changes are \"invisible\" to the\n14\tMCO today - they won't show up in `oc get machineconfig`.  And hence it's not\n15\tas straightforward to make any \"day 2\" changes to them.\n16\t\n17\tIn the future, it's likely the MCO will gain better support for per-node configuration\n18\tas well as tools to more easily manipulate Ignition, so there is less need to edit the\n19\tIgnition JSON directly.\n20\t\n21\t## Q: Why are my workers showing older versions of RHCOS?\n22\t\n23\tToday, the MCO only blocks on upgrades of control plane nodes.  `oc get clusterversion` effectively reports the version of the control plane. \n24\t\n25\tTo watch rollout of worker nodes, you should look at `oc describe machineconfigpool/worker` (as well as other custom pools, if any).\n26\t\n27\t## Q: How does this relate to Machine API?\n28\t\n29\tThere are two fundamental operators in OpenShift 4 that both include \"machine\" in their name:\n30\t\n31\tThe Machine Config Operator (this repository) manages code and configuration \"inside\" the OS (and targets specifcally RHCOS).\n32\t\n33\tThe [Machine API Operator](https://github.com/openshift/machine-api-operator) manages \"machine\" objects which represent underlying IaaS virtual ([or physical](https://github.com/openshift-metal3)) machines.\n34\t\n35\tIn other words, they operate on fundamentally different levels, but they do interact.  For example, both currently will drain a node.  The MCO will drain when it's making changes, and machine API will drain when a machine object is deleted and has an associated node.\n36\t\n37\tAnother linkage between the two is booting an instance; in IaaS scenarios the \"user data\" field (managed by machineAPI) will contain a \"pointer Ignition config\" that points to the Machine Config Server.\n38\t\n39\tHowever, these repositories have distinct teams.  Also, machineAPI is a derivative of a Kubernetes upstream project \"cluster API\", whereas the MCO is not.\n40\t\n41\t## Q: If I change something manually on the host, will the MCO revert it?\n42\t\n43\tUsually, no.  Today, the MCO does not try to claim \"exclusive\" ownership over everything on the host system; it's just not feasible to do.\n44\t\n45\tIf for example you write a daemonset that writes a custom systemd unit into e.g. `/etc/systemd/system`, or do so manually via `ssh`/`oc debug node` - OS upgrades will preserve that change (via libostree), and the MCO will not revert it.  The MCO/MCD only changes files included in `MachineConfigs`, there is no code to look for \"unknown\" files.\n46\t\n47\tAnother case today is that the SDN operator will extract some binaries from its container image and drop them in `/opt` (which is really `/var/opt`).\n48\t\n49\tStated more generally, on an OSTree managed system, all content in `/etc` and `/var` is [preserved by default across upgrades](https://ostreedev.github.io/ostree/adapting-existing/).\n50\t\n51\tFurther, rpm-ostree supports package layering and overrides - these will also be preserved by the MCO (currently).  Although note that there is no current mechanism to trigger a MCO-coordinated drain/reboot, which is particularly relevant for `rpm-ostree install/override` changes.\n52\t\n53\tIf a file that *is* managed by MachineConfig is changed, the MCD will detect this and go degraded.  We go degraded rather than overwrite in order to avoid [reboot loops](https://github.com/openshift/machine-config-operator/pull/245).\n54\t\n55\tIn the future, we would like to harden things more so that these things are more controlled, and ideally avoid having any persistent \"unmanaged\" state.  But it will take significant work to get there; and the status quo means that we can support other operators such as SDN (and e.g. [nmstate](https://github.com/nmstate/kubernetes-nmstate)) that may control parts of the host without the MCO's awareness.\n56\t\n57\t## Q: How do I debug a node failing to join the cluster?\n58\t\n59\tIn clusters that are managed by the [Machine API](https://github.com/openshift/machine-api-operator/), see\n60\t[this question](https://github.com/openshift/machine-api-operator/blob/master/FAQ.md#i-created-a-machine-but-it-never-joined-the-cluster)\n61\tfirst.\n62\t\n63\tA node failing to join can fail broadly speaking at two separate stages; inside\n64\tthe initramfs (Ignition), or in the real root.  If Ignition fails, at the moment\n65\tthis requires accessing the console of the affected machine.  See also\n66\t[this issue](https://github.com/coreos/ignition/issues/585).\n67\t\n68\tIf the system fails in the real root, and you have configured a SSH key for\n69\tthe cluster, you should be able to `ssh` to the node.  A good first command is\n70\t`systemctl --failed`.  Important units to look at would be `machine-config-daemon-firstboot.service`\n71\tand `kubelet.service` - in general, the problem is likely to be some dependency\n72\tof kubelet.\n73\t\n74\t## Q: Can I use the MCO to re-partition or re-install?\n75\t\n76\tNot today.  The [MachineConfig](MachineConfig.md) doc discusses which sections\n77\tof the rendered Ignition can be changed, and that does not include e.g. the Ignition\n78\t`storage` section.  For example, you cannot currently switch an existing worker\n79\tnode to be encrypted or use RAID after the fact - you must re-provision the system.\n80\t\n81\tThe MCO also does not *currently* support explicitly re-provisioning a system \"in place\", however\n82\tthis is likely to be a future feature.  For now, in machineAPI managed environments\n83\tyou should `oc delete` the corresponding `machine` object, or in UPI installations,\n84\tcordon and drain the node, then delete the `node` object and re-provision.\n85\t\n86\tA further problem is that the MCO does not make it easy for *new* nodes to boot\n87\tin the new configuration.\n88\t\n89\tRelated issues:\n90\t\n91\t - https://github.com/openshift/machine-config-operator/issues/1619\n92\t - https://github.com/openshift/machine-config-operator/pull/2035\n93\t\n94\tAll this to say, it's quite hard to change storage layout with the MCO today,\n95\tbut this is a bug.\n96\t\n97\t## Q: Why am I getting \"error: No enabled repositories\" from rpm-ostree?\n98\t\n99\tAs of OCP 4.13 and below, when any extensions are enabled (e.g. `kernel-rt`, `usbguard` etc.)\n100\tthe MCO will provision an rpm-md (yum/dnf) repository only at the time the MCD is making\n101\tchanges to the host system.\n102\t\n103\tThis means that any other invocations of rpm-ostree (e.g. a manual `rpm-ostree initramfs --enable`,\n104\tor `rpm-ostree install` etc.) won't have that repository enabled.\n105\t\n106\tIn some cases, creating an empty/dummy repository in `/etc/yum.repos.d` *may* suffice to work around this bug.\n107\tOr, adding the RHEL UBI repository or [full RHEL entitlements](https://docs.openshift.com/container-platform/4.13/support/remote_health_monitoring/insights-operator-simple-access.html#insights-operator-simple-access) may work.\n108\t\n109\tIn the future, the MCO may change to just leave the repository enabled and avoid this.\n110\t\n111\tHowever, if you're doing deep changes to the host, it may work significantly better\n112\tto instead switch to an [image layering](https://docs.openshift.com/container-platform/4.13/post_installation_configuration/coreos-layering.html) model.\n113\t\n114\t## Q: Does the MCO run on RHEL worker nodes?\n115\t\n116\tYes, RHEL worker nodes will have a instance of the Machine Config Daemon running on them.  However, only a subset of MCO functionality is supported on RHEL worker nodes.  It is possible to create a Machine Config to write files and `systemd` units to RHEL worker nodes, but it is not possible to manage OS updates, kernel arguments, or extensions on RHEL worker nodes.\n117\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01DshDtT9WDTGPZuuhDNzvTz","session_id":"b3810a3c-eea7-4cd5-9b89-22b4f26138cd","uuid":"555cf63b-2df0-4d51-82b8-1bd8ef2341f0","timestamp":"2026-06-22T21:10:31.399Z","subagent_type":"Explore","task_description":"Find MachineConfig YAML examples with files and kernelArguments"}
