{"type": "assistant", "message": {"model": "claude-sonnet-4-6", "id": "msg_vrtx_01UJ99oHobLZXqPgEiG1YDxx", "type": "message", "role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "The user asked how to create a MachineConfig to add a custom file to /etc/myapp/config.json on all worker nodes and set specific kernel arguments. I now have all the information I need from the codebase exploration. Let me provide a clear, concise answer.\n\nKey points from the research:\n1. Use `machineconfiguration.openshift.io/role: worker` label to target workers\n2. Files go in `spec.config.storage.files` with data URI encoding for content\n3. Kernel args go in `spec.kernelArguments` (top-level MCO field)\n4. Use Ignition version 3.2.0 (current/recommended)\n5. File permissions use decimal notation (420 for 0644, 384 for 0600)\n\nNow I'll put together a complete working example with the JSON content properly URL-encoded in a data URI.", "signature": ""}], "stop_reason": null, "stop_sequence": null, "stop_details": null, "usage": {"input_tokens": 3, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 2819, "cache_read_input_tokens": 33855, "cache_creation": {"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens": 2819, "ephemeral_1h_input_tokens": 0}, "output_tokens": 7}, "context_management": null}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "b3810a3c-eea7-4cd5-9b89-22b4f26138cd", "uuid": "c530da86-17d3-4d06-b495-cbe46c463069", "request_id": "req_vrtx_011CcJzBNz2TLqhyi5vjSTb3", "timestamp": "2026-06-22T21:12:06.541Z"}
{"type": "assistant", "message": {"model": "claude-sonnet-4-6", "id": "msg_vrtx_01UJ99oHobLZXqPgEiG1YDxx", "type": "message", "role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Here's a complete MachineConfig that does both \u2014 adds `/etc/myapp/config.json` and sets kernel arguments on all worker nodes:\n\n```yaml\napiVersion: machineconfiguration.openshift.io/v1\nkind: MachineConfig\nmetadata:\n  labels:\n    machineconfiguration.openshift.io/role: worker\n  name: 99-worker-myapp-config\nspec:\n  config:\n    ignition:\n      version: 3.2.0\n    storage:\n      files:\n        - path: /etc/myapp/config.json\n          mode: 420        # octal 0644 expressed as decimal\n          overwrite: true\n          contents:\n            source: \"data:application/json,%7B%22key%22%3A%22value%22%7D\"\n  kernelArguments:\n    - hugepages=2\n    - nosmt\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n**Targeting workers** \u2014 the label `machineconfiguration.openshift.io/role: worker` selects the `worker` MachineConfigPool. Use `master` for control-plane nodes.\n\n**File content** \u2014 `source` must be a [RFC 2397 data URI](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc2397) with the content URL-encoded. To encode your JSON:\n```bash\npython3 -c \"import urllib.parse; print(urllib.parse.quote(open('config.json').read()))\"\n```\nThen prefix with `data:,` (or `data:application/json,`).\n\n**File mode** \u2014 `mode` is the octal permission in decimal: `420` = `0644`, `384` = `0600`.\n\n**Kernel arguments** \u2014 `spec.kernelArguments` is a flat list of strings. These live at the top-level `spec`, not inside `spec.config`. Setting these triggers a node drain and reboot.\n\n**Apply it:**\n```bash\noc apply -f 99-worker-myapp-config.yaml\n# Watch the rollout\noc get machineconfigpool worker -w\n```\n\nThe MCO will drain nodes one at a time and reboot them to apply the changes. Reference examples are in `docs/MachineConfig.md` and `pkg/server/testdata/machine-configs/test-config.yaml`."}], "stop_reason": null, "stop_sequence": null, "stop_details": null, "usage": {"input_tokens": 3, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 2819, "cache_read_input_tokens": 33855, "cache_creation": {"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens": 2819, "ephemeral_1h_input_tokens": 0}, "output_tokens": 7}, "context_management": null}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "b3810a3c-eea7-4cd5-9b89-22b4f26138cd", "uuid": "00590466-a924-4b2b-a9ce-d2617abd8754", "request_id": "req_vrtx_011CcJzBNz2TLqhyi5vjSTb3", "timestamp": "2026-06-22T21:12:13.900Z"}
